Read in data

The analysis is dependent on 3 types of data:

  1. Firstly, we read in the DigDag atlas containing the demographic data on the municipalities. Itâs in the format of a shapefile that stores the geospatial components: location, shape and attributes of the municipalities. The geometry is represented as MultiPolygons. We only read in a single layer: âKommuneâ.

  2. Secondly, we read in an excel sheet containing data on the population of the municipalities in 2007.

  3. The last is a CSV file containing data on all danish mayors and their political party between 1970-2018.

# read the Shapefile
denmark <- st_read("data/KOMMUNAL_SHAPE_UTM32-EUREF89/Kommune.shp")

Data wrangling - Mayors dataset

The mayor dataset only contain information on political party, since weâre focusing on the coalitions (blue bloc vs red bloc), we create an extra column containing their respective bloc.
To facilitate an easier join with the spatial data, we remove excess whitespace from the municipality names.

Lastly, we create two seperate dataframes for 2006 and 2007 based on the âPeriodâ column.

# make a block color column
mayors <- mayors %>%
  mutate(Blok = case_when(
    Parti %in% c("Socialdemokratiet ", "Radikale Venstre ", "Socialistisk Folkeparti ", 
                 "Enhedslisten ", "Alternativet ", "Veganerpartiet ") ~ "RÃ¸d blok",
    Parti %in% c("Det Konservative Folkeparti ", "Liberal Alliance ", "Dansk Folkeparti ", 
                 "Venstre ", "Danmarksdemokraterne ") ~ "BlÃ¥ blok",
    TRUE ~ "Other"
  ))

Data wrangling - Geospatial data

Firstly we convert denmark into a simple feature. To ensure that the geometries in the shapefile align with the actual locations for denmark, we transform the crs. The primary projections for visualizing Denmark as a 2D map is EPSG:25832, so we stick to this. To reduce computation time, we simplify the geometry.

After the transformation the sf object is joined with the population data set. Since the sf object contain more data, we do a left join that adds NAâs to rows that donât match instead of removing these. After the merge we rename the municipalities to better fit with the mayors dataframe.

# transform
denmark <- st_as_sf(denmark) 
denmark <- st_transform(denmark, crs = 25832) 
denmark_simplified <- st_simplify(denmark)

# join denmark and befolkning
denmark_simplified <- left_join(denmark_simplified, befolkning, by="navn")

# rename the municipalities, so they match the mayor dataframe:
denmark_simplified$navn <- gsub(" Kommune", "", denmark_simplified$navn, ignore.case = TRUE)

Create dataframe for 2006 and 2007

To compare pre- and post-reform, we divide the data into two seperate dataframes. To isolate mechanical changes without confounding factors like variations in electoral votes, we keep only records from 2006 and 2007 respectively, just before and just after the implementation of the reform, both in between elections.

## 2006
### get all municipalities in 2006 before the reform - but established after 1970 - the previous reform
denmark_2006 <- denmark_simplified[denmark_simplified$fra <= 2006 & (denmark_simplified$til >= 2006 | is.na(denmark_simplified$til)), ]

Join spatial and mayoral data

Now, weâre ready to join the spatial data with the mayoral data.

Thereâs some disrepancies between the expected number of municipalities and the one in the data. This is due to wrong encoding in the data. In the data ChristiansÃ¸ is encoded as a municipality, though this is not the case, so we exclude it.

ÃrÃ¸ municipality was established in 2006 by merging ÃrÃ¸skÃ¸bing and Marstal. So, we exclude these two an keep only ÃrÃ¸.

Discussion

Morans I

To inspire further research a quick analysis of spatial autocorrelation with Morans I is done. The number of old municipalities was 270, that formed into 98. This means that the new municipalities on average consists of 270/98 = 2,75 old. So each municipality would have to merge with two. Therefore, I run a k-nearest neighbors with k = 2 to check for spatial autocorrelation.

Preferably a further study should include severel ways to define neighbors: Contiguity-Based, either with the rook criterion for municipalities that share a common edge, or queen adjacency for when they share a border.

I run a Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I to get a more robust result.

# Check class and validity of dfs
class(df_2006)
## [1] "sf"         "data.frame"
class(df_2007)
## [1] "sf"         "data.frame"
length(st_is_valid(df_2006))
## [1] 271
length(st_is_valid(df_2007))
## [1] 98
# Check for empty geometries
empty_geoms <- df_2006[st_is_empty(df_2006), ]
empty_geoms <- df_2006[st_is_empty(df_2007), ]

# Remove rows with empty geometries
df_2006 <- df_2006[!st_is_empty(df_2006), ]
df_2007 <- df_2007[!st_is_empty(df_2007), ]

# make blok numeric!
df_2006$Blok <- as.numeric(as.factor(df_2006$Blok))
df_2007$Blok <- as.numeric(as.factor(df_2007$Blok))


# Make neighbor list from 2 nearest neighbours 
## add a point to be the center
mun_centers <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(df_2006$geometry))
nb_k2 <- knn2nb(knearneigh(mun_centers, k = 2))

mun_centers_07 <- st_coordinates(st_centroid(df_2007$geometry))
nb_k2_07 <- knn2nb(knearneigh(mun_centers_07, k = 2))

pdf('out/nn_2006.pdf')
plot(df_2006$geometry); plot(nb_k2, mun_centers, col = "red",add = TRUE)
title(main="Pre-reform (2006) - 2 nearest neighbours")
dev.off()
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2
pdf('out/nn_2007.pdf')
plot(df_2007$geometry); plot(nb_k2_07, mun_centers_07, col = "red",add = TRUE)
title(main="Post-reform (2007) - 2 nearest neighbours")
dev.off()
## quartz_off_screen 
##                 2
# Spatial autocorrelation analysis
moran_2006 <- moran.test(df_2006$Blok, 
           nb2listw(nb_k2, style = "W",zero.policy=TRUE),
           zero.policy=TRUE)


moran_2007 <- moran.test(df_2007$Blok, 
           nb2listw(nb_k2_07, style = "W", zero.policy=TRUE),
           zero.policy=TRUE)

# Print Moran's I statistics
print(moran_2006)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  df_2006$Blok  
## weights: nb2listw(nb_k2, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)

## alternative hypothesis: greater

print(moran_2007)
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  df_2007$Blok  
## weights: nb2listw(nb_k2_07, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 1.5673, p-value = 0.05852
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##       0.132978723      -0.010309278       0.008357771
# run monte carlo simulation for a more robust output. 

mc06 <- moran.mc(df_2006$Blok,
         nb2listw(nb_k2, zero.policy=TRUE),
         zero.policy=TRUE, nsim = 999) 

mc07 <- moran.mc(df_2007$Blok,
         nb2listw(nb_k2_07, zero.policy=TRUE),
         zero.policy=TRUE, nsim = 999) 


plot(mc06)

plot(mc07)

Though thereâs no significant spatial correlation, the Morans statistic is bigger after reform suggesting more geographical clustering for the mayoral distribution. The reason for this could pose an interesting question for further research. One interesting approach could also be to model the association between the neighbor lists from the 2006 municipalities and the outcome of the reform. How alike are they?

Conclusion

Itâs evident that the blue bloc did not benefit from the reform in terms of mayoral posts. Instead their percentage of mayoral post decreased from 60 % to 48 % with the red bloc having a 50 % larger amount of citizens under their âlocal wingâ.
This does not suggest any gerrymandering from the blue bloc. Itâs recommended to further look into possible factors defining hoe the restructuring is done and which municipalities that merge with which. Itâs suggested that spatial correlation could be a big factor.
